<td width=3D"514" height=3D"309">
<h1 align=3D"center">Mass and Weight</h1>
 <p> The mass of an object is a fundamental property of the object; a numer=
ical measure of its inertia; a fundamental measure of the amount of matter =
in the object. Definitions of mass often seem circular because it is such a=
 fundamental quantity that it is hard to define in terms of something else.=
 All <a href=3D"http://hyperphysics.phy-astr.gsu.edu/hbase/units.html#unit"=
>mechanical quantities</a> can be defined in terms of mass, length, and tim=
e. The usual symbol for mass is m and its SI unit is the kilogram. While th=
e mass is normally considered to be an unchanging property of an object, at=
 speeds approaching the speed of light one must consider the increase in th=
e <a href=3D"http://hyperphysics.phy-astr.gsu.edu/hbase/relativ/tdil.html#c=
3">relativistic mass</a>. </p>
     <p>The weight of an object is the force of <a href=3D"http://hyperphys=
ics.phy-astr.gsu.edu/hbase/grav.html#grav">gravity</a> on the object and ma=
y be defined as the mass times the <a href=3D"http://hyperphysics.phy-astr.=
gsu.edu/hbase/orbv.html#eg">acceleration of gravity</a>, w =3D mg. Since th=
e weight is a <a href=3D"http://hyperphysics.phy-astr.gsu.edu/hbase/force.h=
tml#defor">force</a>, its SI unit is the newton. <a href=3D"http://hyperphy=
sics.phy-astr.gsu.edu/hbase/dens.html#dens">Density</a> is mass/volume. </p=
>=20
